alloc.haxe_doc: Returns a new `Bytes` instance with the given `length`. The values of the bytes are not initialized and may not be zero.

ofString.haxe_doc: Returns the `Bytes` representation of the given `String`, using the specified encoding (UTF-8 by default).

fill.haxe_doc: Sets `len` consecutive bytes starting from index `pos` of `this` instance to `value`.

sub.haxe_doc: Returns a new `Bytes` instance that contains a copy of `len` bytes of `this` instance, starting at index `pos`.

getDouble.haxe_doc: Returns the IEEE double-precision value at the given position `pos` (in little-endian encoding). Result is unspecified if `pos` is outside the bounds.

getFloat.haxe_doc: Returns the IEEE single-precision value at the given position `pos` (in little-endian encoding). Result is unspecified if `pos` is outside the bounds.

setFloat.haxe_doc: Stores the given IEEE single-precision value `v` at the given position `pos` in little-endian encoding. Result is unspecified if writing outside of bounds.

getString.haxe_doc: Returns the `len`-bytes long string stored at the given position `pos`, interpreted with the given `encoding` (UTF-8 by default).

toString.haxe_doc: Returns a `String` representation of the bytes interpreted as UTF-8.

toHex.haxe_doc: Returns a hexadecimal `String` representation of the bytes of `this` instance.

class.haxe_doc: Allows one to encode/decode String and bytes using Base64 encoding.
Allows one to encode/decode String and bytes using a power of two base dictionary.
Creates a MD5 of a String.

ft.haxe_doc: Perform the appropriate triplet combination function for the current iteration

kt.haxe_doc: Determine the appropriate additive constant for the current iteration

class.haxe_doc: Creates a Sha1 of a String.

sort.haxe_doc:
Sorts Array `a` according to the comparison function `cmp`, where `cmp(x,y)` returns 0 if `x == y`, a positive Int if `x > y` and a negative Int if `x < y`.
This operation modifies Array `a` in place.
This operation is stable: The order of equal elements is preserved.
If `a` or `cmp` are null, the result is unspecified.

class.haxe_doc: ArraySort provides a stable implementation of merge sort through its `sort` method. It should be used instead of `Array.sort` in cases where the order of equal elements has to be retained on all targets.

set.haxe_doc:
Binds `key` to `value`.
If `key` is already bound to a value, that binding disappears.
If `key` is null, the result is unspecified.

get.haxe_doc:
Returns the value `key` is bound to.
If `key` is not bound to any value, `null` is returned.
If `key` is null, the result is unspecified.

new.haxe_doc: Creates a new BalancedTree, which is initially empty.

class.haxe_doc:
BalancedTree allows key-value mapping with arbitrary keys, as long as they can be ordered. By default, `Reflect.compare` is used in the `compare` method, which can be overridden in subclasses.
Operations have a logarithmic average and worst-case cost.
Iteration over keys and values, using `keys` and `iterator` respectively, are in-order.

remove.haxe_doc:

If `v` is found by checking standard equality, it is removed from `this` List and the function returns true.
Otherwise, false is returned.

class.haxe_doc:

@see https://haxe.org/manual/std-List.html

abstract.haxe_doc:

Maps can also be created with `[key1 => value1, key2 => value2]` syntax.

Copies `length` of elements from `src` Vector, beginning at `srcPos` to `dest` Vector, beginning at `destPos`

print.haxe_doc:
Encodes `o`'s value and returns the resulting JSON string.
If `replacer` is given and is not null, it is used to retrieve actual object to be encoded. The `replacer` function takes two parameters, the key and the value being encoded. Initial key value is an empty string.
If `space` is given and is not null, the result will be pretty-printed. Successive levels will be indented by this string.

length.haxe_doc: The length of the buffer in bytes.

getBytes.haxe_doc: Returns either a copy or a reference of the current bytes. Once called, the buffer should no longer be used.

bigEndian.haxe_doc:
Endianness (word byte order) used when reading numbers.
If `true`, big-endian is used, otherwise `little-endian` is used.

readBytes.haxe_doc:
Read `len` bytes and write them into `s` to the position specified by `pos`.
Returns the actual length of read data that can be smaller than `len`.
See `readFullBytes` that tries to read the exact amount of specified bytes.

close.haxe_doc:
Close the input source.
Behaviour while reading after calling this method is unspecified.

readAll.haxe_doc:
Read and return all available data.
The `bufsize` optional argument specifies the size of chunks by which data is read. Its default value is target-specific.

readFullBytes.haxe_doc:
Read `len` bytes and write them into `s` to the position specified by `pos`.
Unlike `readBytes`, this method tries to read the exact `len` amount of bytes.

readUntil.haxe_doc:
Read a string until a character code specified by `end` is occurred.
The final character is not included in the resulting string.

readFloat.haxe_doc:
Read a 32-bit floating point number.

normalizeScaleOrient.haxe_doc: Convert centimeters to meters and axis to Z-up (Maya FBX export)

getAnimationNames.haxe_doc: Returns an array of names with all animations present in FBX file.

getIndexes.haxe_doc: Decode polygon informations into triangle indexes and vertices indexes. Returns vidx, which is the list of vertices indexes and iout which is the index buffer for the full vertex model

toSdfFont.haxe_doc: Load and cache Signed Distance Field font with specified size, channel, alphaCutoff and smoothing. ( default : initial size, red, 0.5, 1 / 32 ) For more information on SDF texture generation refer to this page: https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/wiki/Distance-field-fonts For more information on MSDF texture generation refer to this page: https://github.com/Chlumsky/msdfgen

ALLOW_NPOT.haxe_doc: Specify if we will automatically convert non-power-of-two textures to power-of-two.

DEFAULT_ASYNC.haxe_doc: Forces async decoding for images if available on the target platform.

onEnd.haxe_doc: onEnd() is called when a sound which does not loop has finished playing or when we switch buffer in a queue or when a sound which is streamed loops.

queueSound.haxe_doc: Add a sound to the queue. When the current sound is finished playing, the next one will seamlessly continue. This will also trigger an onEnd() event.

load.haxe_doc: Some platforms might require some data to be loaded before we can start decoding. Use load() and wait for onEnd to make sure that the sound data and the correct number of samples is available. onEnd() might be called back immediately if the data is already available.

BUFFER_STREAM_SPLIT.haxe_doc: Allows to decode big streaming buffers over X split frames. 0 to disable

getAll.haxe_doc: Returns iterator with all active instances of a Sound at the call time.

class.haxe_doc: On platforms that don't have native support for OpenAL, the Driver uses this emulator that only requires a NativeChannel implementation

getLinkShader.haxe_doc: Creates a shader that generate the output requested.

class.haxe_doc: Evaluator : will substitute some variables (usually constants) by their runtime value and will evaluate and reduce the expression, unroll loops, etc.

signature.haxe_doc: Signature of the resulting HxSL code. Several shaders with the different specification might still get the same resulting signature.

uid.haxe_doc: The user id for the file owner.

size.haxe_doc: The size of the file, in bytes.

rdev.haxe_doc: The device type on which stat resides (special files only).

nlink.haxe_doc: The number of hard links to stat.

mtime.haxe_doc: The last modification time for the file.

mode.haxe_doc: The permission bits of stat. The meaning of the bits is platform dependent.

gid.haxe_doc: The user group id for the file owner.

dev.haxe_doc: The device on which stat resides.

ctime.haxe_doc: The creation time for the file (not all file systems support this).

atime.haxe_doc: The last access time for the file (when enabled by the file system).

typedef.haxe_doc: File information, as given by `sys.FileSystem.stat`.

exists.haxe_doc: Returns `true` if the file or directory specified by `path` exists.

rename.haxe_doc:
Renames/moves the file or directory specified by `path` to `newPath`.
If `path` is not a valid file system entry, or if it is not accessible, or if `newPath` is not accessible, an exception is thrown.

stat.haxe_doc: Returns `FileStat` information for the file or directory specified by `path`.

fullPath.haxe_doc: Returns the full path of the file or directory specified by `relPath`, which is relative to the current working directory. Symlinks will be followed and the path will be normalized.

absolutePath.haxe_doc: Returns the full path of the file or directory specified by `relPath`, which is relative to the current working directory. The path doesn't have to exist.

isDirectory.haxe_doc:
Returns `true` if the file or directory specified by `path` is a directory.
If `path` is not a valid file system entry or if its destination is not accessible, an exception is thrown.

createDirectory.haxe_doc:
Creates a directory specified by `path`.
This method is recursive: The parent directories don't have to exist.
If the directory cannot be created, an exception is thrown.

deleteFile.haxe_doc:
Deletes the file specified by `path`.
If `path` does not denote a valid file, or if that file cannot be deleted, an exception is thrown.

deleteDirectory.haxe_doc:
Deletes the directory specified by `path`. Only empty directories can be deleted.
If `path` does not denote a valid directory, or if that directory cannot be deleted, an exception is thrown.

readDirectory.haxe_doc:
Returns the names of all files and directories in the directory specified by `path`. `"."` and `".."` are not included in the output.
If `path` does not denote a valid directory, an exception is thrown.

class.haxe_doc:
This class provides information about files and directories.
If `null` is passed as a file path to any function in this class, the result is unspecified, and may differ from target to target.
See `sys.io.File` for the complementary file API.

getContent.haxe_doc:
Retrieves the content of the file specified by `path` as a String.
If the file does not exist or can not be read, an exception is thrown.
`sys.FileSystem.exists` can be used to check for existence.
If `path` is null, the result is unspecified.

saveContent.haxe_doc:
Stores `content` in the file specified by `path`.
If the file cannot be written to, an exception is thrown.
If `path` or `content` are null, the result is unspecified.

getBytes.haxe_doc:
Retrieves the binary content of the file specified by `path`.
If the file does not exist or can not be read, an exception is thrown.
`sys.FileSystem.exists` can be used to check for existence.
If `path` is null, the result is unspecified.

saveBytes.haxe_doc:
Stores `bytes` in the file specified by `path` in binary mode.
If the file cannot be written to, an exception is thrown.
If `path` or `bytes` are null, the result is unspecified.

read.haxe_doc:
Returns an `FileInput` handle to the file specified by `path`.
If `binary` is true, the file is opened in binary mode. Otherwise it is opened in non-binary mode.
If the file does not exist or can not be read, an exception is thrown.
Operations on the returned `FileInput` handle read on the opened file.
File handles should be closed via `FileInput.close` once the operation is complete.
If `path` is null, the result is unspecified.

write.haxe_doc:
Returns an `FileOutput` handle to the file specified by `path`.
If `binary` is true, the file is opened in binary mode. Otherwise it is opened in non-binary mode.
If the file cannot be written to, an exception is thrown.
Operations on the returned `FileOutput` handle write to the opened file. If the file existed, its previous content is overwritten.
File handles should be closed via `FileOutput.close` once the operation is complete.
If `path` is null, the result is unspecified.

append.haxe_doc: Similar to `sys.io.File.write`, but appends to the file if it exists instead of overwriting its contents.

update.haxe_doc: Similar to `sys.io.File.append`. While `append` can only seek or write starting from the end of the file's previous contents, `update` can seek to any position, so the file's previous contents can be selectively overwritten.

copy.haxe_doc:
Copies the contents of the file specified by `srcPath` to the file specified by `dstPath`.
If the `srcPath` does not exist or cannot be read, or if the `dstPath` file cannot be written to, an exception is thrown.
If the file at `dstPath` exists, its contents are overwritten.
If `srcPath` or `dstPath` are null, the result is unspecified.

class.haxe_doc:
API for reading and writing files.
See `sys.FileSystem` for the complementary file system API.
Use `sys.io.File.read` to create a `FileInput`.
Use `sys.io.File.write` to create a `FileOutput`.
